Dual-LLM Home AI Orchestration Plan (Draft)
Status: Exploratory / Not Committed

Objective
Design a local AI system capable of assisting with software engineering and automation tasks across multiple domains, including:

Game logic development
Blender scripting and asset workflow support
PL/SQL query design and optimization
Oracle APEX application development
Cross-device accessibility (desktop, mobile, browser)
The system prioritizes correctness, structured reasoning, and workflow automation over raw conversational speed.

Core Architecture Overview
The system is composed of three primary layers:
2.1 Inference Layer (LLMs)

Model A: Fast Planner (7B–13B class)
  Purpose: task decomposition, routing, lightweight generation
Model B: Reasoner / Critic (13B–30B class)
  Purpose: validation, debugging, deeper reasoning, review
Both models operate independently but are coordinated via an orchestrator.
2.2 Orchestration Layer
Responsible for:

Managing task decomposition
Routing prompts to correct model
Handling iteration loops
Maintaining state between steps
Coordinating tool execution
This layer acts as the “control plane” of the system.
2.3 Tool / Execution Layer
External systems used by the LLMs:

Code execution (CLI, scripts)
Git operations
Database queries (PL/SQL)
Browser automation / APEX interaction support
Blender scripting interface
File system operations
Tools provide ground truth verification and execution capability.

Agent Role Structure (Logical, Not Physical Models)
The system defines roles rather than separate always-running agents:
3.1 Planner Role

Breaks down user request into structured steps
Identifies required tools and constraints
3.2 Executor Role

Produces code, scripts, or actions
Interacts with tool layer
3.3 Critic Role

Reviews outputs for correctness
Detects logical, syntactical, or structural issues
3.4 Repair Loop Role

Iteratively corrects outputs based on critic feedback
Note: These roles are executed dynamically using 1–2 underlying models.

Concurrency Model
The system supports limited concurrency:

Parallel execution of tool operations (non-LLM tasks)
Sequential or semi-parallel LLM inference
Task pipelining across roles (planner/executor/critic overlap)
True multi-LLM parallel inference is constrained by GPU VRAM and compute limits.
Expected safe concurrency:

1–2 active LLM inference streams
Multiple parallel tool operations
Expected Performance Characteristics (High-Level)
5.1 Game Logic Development

Small features: seconds to ~3 minutes
Medium systems: ~3–10 minutes iterative cycles
Large systems: 10–30 minutes structured breakdown
5.2 Blender Workflow Support

Simple scripting tasks: ~30 seconds–2 minutes per iteration
Full asset pipelines: 10–25+ minutes iterative refinement
5.3 PL/SQL Development

Simple queries: 5–15 seconds
Complex queries: 30–120 seconds with refinement loops
5.4 Oracle APEX Development

Small UI/logic fixes: 20–60 seconds
Multi-page systems: 5–15+ minutes iterative cycles
Hardware Considerations
6.1 GPU (Primary Constraint)

Determines model size and inference speed
24GB VRAM class suitable for 7B–30B models
6.2 CPU (Secondary Constraint)

Impacts orchestration, tool execution, and concurrency
Becomes important when multiple workflows run in parallel
6.3 RAM

Recommended 32–64GB minimum for stable multi-service operation
Supports vector databases, caching, and orchestration layers
Scaling Path
Phase 1:

Single fast model + basic orchestration
Phase 2:

Dual-model system (planner + critic)
Tool integration layer
Phase 3:

Full agent orchestration
Memory system (RAG/vector DB)
Parallel tool execution
Phase 4:

Optional CPU upgrade for higher concurrency and orchestration throughput
Key Risks / Limitations
Increased latency vs single-model chat systems
GPU memory constraints limit true parallel LLM execution
Orchestration complexity increases system fragility
Tool integration is the primary source of system failure, not the models
Core Design Principle
The system does not rely on a single large model for intelligence.
Instead, it distributes reasoning across:

decomposition (planner)
execution (tool + LLM)
verification (critic)
Goal: improve correctness and reduce iteration cycles in engineering workflows.
End of Draft.
Issues & Recommended Changes (Review Addendum)
This section highlights architectural gaps, risk areas, and recommended refinements for production-grade implementation.

Model Role Overlap (Planning vs Critic ambiguity)
Issue:
Planner and Critic responsibilities partially overlap in reasoning validation, which can cause redundant computation or conflicting outputs.
Recommended change:
Planner should ONLY decompose and structure tasks (no validation logic).
Critic should ONLY evaluate outputs against explicit criteria (correctness, edge cases, constraints).
Introduce a shared validation schema to prevent subjective critique.
Repair Loop Oscillation Risk
Issue:
2–3 iteration repair loops may still produce oscillation (fix → break → fix cycles), especially in SQL and APEX workflows.
Recommended change:
Add a hard "replan trigger": after 2 failed critic cycles, discard execution plan and re-run Planner.
Store failure reason taxonomy (schema mismatch, logic error, tool failure).
Critic Model Overuse (Latency Bottleneck)
Issue:
Using 13B–30B models frequently for critique can dominate runtime and degrade system responsiveness.
Recommended change:
Introduce tiered critic system:
  * Fast Critic (8B–13B) for routine checks

  * Deep Critic (30B+) only for:

    * production-level code

    * deployment actions

    * database modifications

Route based on task risk score.
Tool Layer Fragility (Primary System Risk)
Issue:
Tool execution failures may be incorrectly interpreted as model reasoning failures.
Recommended change:
Standardize tool output schema:
  * success flag

  * structured error codes

  * execution trace log

Separate:
  * LLM failure

  * tool failure

  * environment failure

Blender Integration Under-specification
Issue:
Blender is treated as stateless scripting environment, but it is inherently stateful (scene graph dependency).
Recommended change:
Introduce scene checkpointing:
  * export/import JSON or .blend snapshots

Require deterministic rebuild scripts instead of incremental mutation where possible
Oracle APEX Automation Risk (UI Volatility)
Issue:
APEX UI changes can break Playwright-based automation and mimic model hallucination errors.
Recommended change:
Prefer backend-first interaction (PL/SQL APIs) over UI automation where possible
If UI automation is required:
  * introduce selector abstraction layer

  * avoid brittle DOM selectors

Missing Explicit Memory Architecture
Issue:
Memory system is only partially defined (RAG mentioned but not structured).
Recommended change:
Define 3-layer memory model:
Working Memory: current LangGraph state
Episodic Memory: past task executions + outcomes
Semantic Memory: embeddings / retrieval layer
Concurrency Model Underutilization
Issue:
Current design limits concurrency to LLM streams, but underutilizes parallel tool execution potential.
Recommended change:
Explicitly define tool execution worker pool
Allow parallel non-LLM operations (DB + file + API + Blender subprocess)
Introduce async task DAG scheduling
Missing Risk Scoring System (Recommended Addition)
Issue:
System treats all tasks with equal orchestration depth, leading to unnecessary overhead for simple tasks.
Recommended change:
Introduce task risk scoring:
Low: single model execution
Medium: planner + executor
High: full planner → executor → critic → repair loop
CPU Upgrade Timing Undefined
Issue:
CPU upgrade is mentioned but not tied to measurable triggers.
Recommended change:
Define upgrade thresholds:
sustained multi-workflow concurrency bottlenecks
tool execution latency dominates >30% of total task time
RAG/vector workloads exceed single-node responsiveness
End of Review Addendum.


